1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:01,976
What if an AI couldn't be copied?

2
00:00:01,976 --> 00:00:06,826
What if it lived inside one specific computer, and refused to work anywhere else?

3
00:00:06,826 --> 00:00:10,479
Today we show you exactly that, without any special hardware.

4
00:00:10,479 --> 00:00:12,096
Just two ordinary machines.

5
00:00:14,000 --> 00:00:20,076
We have two physically identical machines: same model, same memory, same storage, same microcode.

6
00:00:20,076 --> 00:00:23,898
Inside each one runs an AI that reads its own physical state.

7
00:00:23,898 --> 00:00:24,650
Temperature.

8
00:00:24,650 --> 00:00:26,905
Microsecond-level timing variations.

9
00:00:26,905 --> 00:00:28,409
Memory refresh patterns.

10
00:00:28,409 --> 00:00:30,225
Five signals nobody can hide.

11
00:00:30,225 --> 00:00:36,991
Together they form a hardware fingerprint, unique to the silicon itself, born from manufacturing tolerances.

12
00:00:40,000 --> 00:00:42,818
We ask each AI a simple question: who are you?

13
00:00:42,818 --> 00:00:49,314
Each model reads its live hardware signature, compares it to the substrate it was trained on, and answers.

14
00:00:49,314 --> 00:00:51,704
On ikaros, the model says: I am ikaros.

15
00:00:51,704 --> 00:00:54,339
On daedalus, the model says: I am daedalus.

16
00:00:54,339 --> 00:00:55,259
Both confident.

17
00:00:55,259 --> 00:00:56,055
Both correct.

18
00:00:56,055 --> 00:00:58,936
Forty out of forty identifications, every time.

19
00:01:02,000 --> 00:01:03,266
Now watch carefully.

20
00:01:03,266 --> 00:01:06,241
We copy the model file from ikaros to daedalus.

21
00:01:06,241 --> 00:01:06,875
Same file.

22
00:01:06,875 --> 00:01:07,698
Same weights.

23
00:01:07,698 --> 00:01:08,584
Same training.

24
00:01:08,584 --> 00:01:09,977
Only the body changes.

25
00:01:09,977 --> 00:01:14,662
On daedalus, the transplanted model boots up and tries to identify itself.

26
00:01:14,662 --> 00:01:18,714
But the live signature it reads belongs to daedalus, not ikaros.

27
00:01:18,714 --> 00:01:23,146
The model still claims to be ikaros, because that is where it learned.

28
00:01:23,146 --> 00:01:25,615
But the verifier sees a different chip.

29
00:01:25,615 --> 00:01:27,641
The two signatures do not match.

30
00:01:27,641 --> 00:01:28,970
The protocol rejects.

31
00:01:28,970 --> 00:01:31,630
The AI is bound to its original substrate.

32
00:01:31,630 --> 00:01:33,656
It refuses to run anywhere else.

33
00:01:37,000 --> 00:01:38,738
Could an attacker fake this?

34
00:01:38,738 --> 00:01:40,165
We tried three attacks.

35
00:01:40,165 --> 00:01:41,034
First: replay.

36
00:01:41,034 --> 00:01:44,325
Record a real ikaros signature, then replay it later.

37
00:01:44,325 --> 00:01:47,553
Rejected ninety-nine point four percent of the time.

38
00:01:47,553 --> 00:01:53,822
Each verification uses a fresh challenge nonce, so the recorded signature is for the wrong challenge.

39
00:01:53,822 --> 00:01:55,498
Second: a random signature.

40
00:01:55,498 --> 00:01:57,981
Rejected ninety-nine point four percent.

41
00:01:57,981 --> 00:02:00,526
Random data does not match any real chip.

42
00:02:00,526 --> 00:02:01,706
Third: brute force.

43
00:02:01,706 --> 00:02:10,397
The attacker would need to record a valid signature for every possible challenge, which is two to the sixty-third, roughly nine quintillion.

44
00:02:10,397 --> 00:02:11,079
Infeasible.

45
00:02:14,000 --> 00:02:19,711
Why is this different from Apple's Private Cloud Compute, or NVIDIA's Confidential Compute?

46
00:02:19,711 --> 00:02:25,863
Those require a special trusted chip from Apple or NVIDIA, and you have to trust the manufacturer.

47
00:02:25,863 --> 00:02:29,378
Intel TDX and SGX require Intel silicon and Intel's PKI.

48
00:02:29,378 --> 00:02:31,387
TPM requires a dedicated module.

49
00:02:31,387 --> 00:02:33,270
FabricCrypt uses none of that.

50
00:02:33,270 --> 00:02:34,274
No special chip.

51
00:02:34,274 --> 00:02:35,153
No vendor key.

52
00:02:35,153 --> 00:02:37,726
Just commodity AMD silicon, plus physics.

53
00:02:37,726 --> 00:02:40,927
Per-die AI attestation on hardware you already own.

54
00:02:44,000 --> 00:02:44,757
Limitations.

55
00:02:44,757 --> 00:02:46,146
We tested two chassis.

56
00:02:46,146 --> 00:02:47,599
Replication is welcome.

57
00:02:47,599 --> 00:02:52,019
The protocol proves who ran the inference, not what the inference was.

58
00:02:52,019 --> 00:02:55,240
This is not a replacement for confidential compute.

59
00:02:55,240 --> 00:02:58,207
It is a primitive for verifiable AI provenance.

60
00:03:00,000 --> 00:03:01,513
An AI bound to its body.

61
00:03:01,513 --> 00:03:02,395
No vendor key.

62
00:03:02,395 --> 00:03:03,404
No special chip.

63
00:03:03,404 --> 00:03:04,223
Just physics.

